##EPIDEMIOLOGIST OXFORD: Will Britain's strategy succeed at the worst case scenario? | exclusive interview

Micro Signal deeptechchina

Function description DeepTech is a full-chain content, service, data and investment and financing platform focusing on the emerging technology industrialization, and is committed to building a global network of scientific and technological innovation cooperation.

As a big scientific country, how did Britain deal with the new crown disease? Will they be able to follow a different, less costly and more effective path to epidemic prevention than China? So we spoke with Chen Zhengming, an epidemiologist and tenured professor at Oxford University.

The UK confirmed its first imported new crown patient from China at the end of January. As of March 8,273 new cases had been diagnosed, ranking sixth in Europe, behind Italy, France, Germany, Spain and Switzerland. The second death occurred on 6 March in a man in his 80s.

Following the outbreak in Wuhan, British Airways and Virgin Atlantic suspended all flights to and from mainland China in late January, following which the British government sent special planes to evacuate more than 300 people from Wuhan and surrounding areas.

Despite this, Chen said, Britain as a whole is relatively calm and rational. The UK government requires 14 days of home self-isolation for travellers or returning citizens who arrive on other flights or routes, such as those from Hubei Province, or from other parts of China, but have associated symptoms such as fever. Other than that, there are no other restrictions or regulations.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | trend in daily number of new crown patients in the UK. (Source: BBC)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | trend of daily increase in number of new coronary patients outside China. (Source: BBC)

The outbreak remained relatively stable throughout February, with just over 20 people confirmed, most of them imported, and close contacts isolated for a short period of time, effectively preventing the spread of the epidemic. The number of infections in the UK has also risen rapidly in the past week or so as the Italian epidemic has worsened sharply and imported cases have increased. To this end, the British government introduced a complete epidemic prevention plan to deal with the spread of the epidemic.

The government's four-stage plan includes containment, delay, research and mitigation. The current epidemic prevention policy remains focused on the containment phase, focusing on the timely diagnosis and tracing and isolation of all close contacts. If the epidemic deteriorates further and there is widespread community spread, consideration will be given to moving to the second phase of the epidemic prevention, namely the delay and "social isolation" phase. Relevant measures include suspension of schools, markets and work to avoid a major outbreak of the epidemic in the short term, and as much as possible to delay the summer, so that medical institutions can have more adequate resources to deal with patient care.

In the face of new outbreaks, the government should keep the Seek truth from facts informed of the development of the epidemic, including the worst possible outcome, as well as relevant individual and community preventive measures, Chen said, this may be the best "vaccine" to avoid panic and contagion.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Global distribution of new crown disease. (Source: HEALTHMAP)

"This is not a small-scale battle, and the UK is preparing for the worst. "

DEEPTECH: Why has Italy become the worst affected region in Europe, with such a high case fatality rate among infected people?

Chen Zhengming: Italy became the disaster area to have the accidental factor, may also have its inevitable factor.

First of all, Italy is a popular tourist destination, with more than 1.5 million Chinese tourists visiting each year, compared with a record 270,000 Chinese visitors to the UK.

There is also a very special situation, currently living in Italy, work, settlement of Wenzhou people about one hundred thousand, is a very large group, around the Spring Festival population flow is very frequent. Wenzhou is also the most affected city in China outside of Hubei, where people from Wenzhou do most of their business. This invisible increase in the spread of the epidemic in Italy risk rate. (as of March 9, Wenzhou had 504 confirmed cases, the most of any Chinese city outside Hubei Province.)

Italy did nothing at the start of the outbreak until Jan. 30, when it suspended flights to mainland China, Hong Kong and Taiwan. Before this, a large number of tourists from Wenzhou or other parts of China have arrived in Italy. Moreover, even a flight ban would not completely block the spread of the disease, especially in Europe, where population movements are so high that people can still freely enter Italy from other European countries.

In addition, the new coronavirus mainly through the droplets and close contact, while the Italians are very warm people, have the habit of meeting each other to hug and kiss, which increases the possibility of transmission of the virus.

The new coronavirus mortality rate in Italy is higher than that in China, about 4% . The average age of the current deaths is 81 years, and most patients had other health problems during their lifetime, which may have contributed to the high risk of death.

DEEPTECH: Is there an imported case from Italy in the UK?

Chen Zhengming: the vast majority of the outbreaks in the UK are imported, especially travellers from key areas such as China, Italy and the Diamond Princess, as well as super-infectees returning from business meetings at the Grand Hyatt Hotel in Singapore.

The first wave was of new champions from China, the second mainly from continental Europe. In late February, when the students are on vacation, there is a 10-day vacation or so, many people go to Italy to go skiing. Recently, a lot of patients have occurred in succession and are related to Italy.

The UK currently has a relatively young population, so the case fatality rate is not as high as in Italy. Most people returning from holidays across Italy are now isolated at home, but the situation is not promising as to whether widespread community transmission can be effectively prevented.

DEEPTECH: Is it customary for the British government to respond to new outbreaks with a four-step action plan that seems to be in place?

Chen Zhengming: The United Kingdom is more advocating science, attach importance to science, in response to major public health events, like to say science rules, say science routines.

Evidence-based decision-making is important. At the time of 1990s, for example, there was a lot of public health research in the UK on how cows spread the virus, and the evidence was constantly changing the approach. In response to the new coronavirus outbreak, the British government has brought together a large number of experts, including epidemiologists, public health and clinical experts, to come up with a scientific action plan to guide the government's decision making, not Rush into it.

It was not a skirmish, and Britain was prepared for the worst. The prime minister, Johnson, said the possibility of a fifth of the workforce suffering from the disease could not be ruled out. Of course, that's the worst thing that can happen. From a scientific point of view, this is the way of the Seek truth from facts, which should tell people what the worst possible outcome is and trust their judgment.

"Some of China's measures would work in the UK as well, some would not and the social costs would be too high. "

DEEPTECH: There have been reports that the UK has loosened up both internally and externally, which seems to be a bit like Singapore.

Chen Zhengming: I think the current epidemic is still a transitional stage, and will continue to deteriorate, the later on the British government and the medical system is a great challenge. With so many patients suffering from the common cold and flu, and a shortage of doctors and nurses (there are tens of thousands of vacancies) , the system is already under strain. The future must be based on the development of the epidemic to study and gradually adjust prevention and control measures, as well as make the necessary trade-offs.

Some of China's measures are equally feasible in the UK, while others are unworkable and socially costly. Britain, with the exception of London, has a lower population density, which is relatively good for disease control and Prevention. In contrast, British communities, which are walled off and well connected, can not be managed in the same closed way as in China, and people may not agree.

DEEPTECH: What has UK academia and science done since the outbreak of the new crown disease?

Chen Zhengming: the Medical Research Council in the UK launched a # 20m research programme in early February to carry out vaccine, drug and epidemiological research. Recently, the government has invested more funds to speed up research and development steps and efforts.

On the scientific front, Oxford and the Imperial College London have done a lot of work, including vaccines and disease prediction. In mid-january, a team from imperial was able to assess the Wuhan outbreak with some accuracy, based on limited data on the number of people infected overseas. Oxford's infectious disease research strength is very strong, the new coronavirus vaccine research in the international leading position, has now been produced in small quantities, May, may be able to enter human trials in June. In addition, a team from Oxford worked with the CAO BIN team at the China Japan Friendship Hospital to participate in the REDESIVIR clinical trial.

DEEPTECH: How has the understanding of British society changed since the outbreak of the new crown disease?

Chen Zhengming: recently, the density of media reports has obviously increased. In addition to reporting on the epidemic and the government's actions, there are many experts who interpret it. In addition, there are a large number of public service advertising, health education. Its main purpose is to let the public fully informed, the correct understanding of the disease and the prevention and control measures should be taken.

Wuhan's initial outbreak was a lesson. Because people didn't know, they were blind, they felt fine, and once the announcement of the human-to-human transmission and the closure of the city, large numbers of people panicked and rushed to the hospitals, which led to a second and third wave of virus transmission and hospital cross-infection.

Of course it has to do with the health care system. The UK now has a high-throughput telephone line that collects information and offers advice in case of suspicious symptoms. The local public health agency sends someone to the House or sends the patient to a designated facility for a sample. This largely avoids the risk of cross-infection by going straight to the hospital.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The UK government's advice for those who suspect they have a new coronavirus: don't go to a hospital, community clinic or emergency room. Call first on a dedicated line, isolate yourself, report information, test, and follow the advice of a health care worker. (Source: BBC)

DEEPTECH: What does the British public think about wearing a mask? Is it consistent with the World Health Organization's recommendation to wear masks?

Chen Zhengming: There are obvious cultural differences between the East and the West in wearing masks. I've lived here for 30 years, and I've never seen anyone wear a mask. Only patients to the hospital to see a doctor, in order to prevent sneezing droplets, only need to wear a mask, for normal people is not necessary to wear a mask. If you wear a mask on the street, the British people will think it is dangerous for a sick person to walk around. So there was some conflict.

With just over 200 confirmed cases out of nearly 70m people in the UK, it would be unrealistic for everyone to wear a mask and the effect on preventing viral infections would not be significant. The new guidelines for personal protection against coronaviruses issued by the World Health Organization recommend wearing a mask only when symptoms occur or when caring for suspected or confirmed patients. Many people do not wash their hands wearing a mask, or wear a mask in the wrong way, but will increase the risk of infection. Of course, as the epidemic changes, people's psychology and risk expectations may change significantly.

DEEPTECH: Masks are not a minor issue in China, but there are some secondary issues, such as not wearing a mask can not enter supermarkets, can not enter shopping malls, and even in the street can not wear a mask will be arrested. Is China overstating the role of face masks?

Chen Zhengming: we just started to ignore the epidemic, after the attention is panic, so desperate to seize the phenomenon of masks. For the most part, wearing masks is an important psychological relief, especially in areas where the epidemic is now well under control. It is not easy for the whole society to take off the mask completely. It may need a lot of preparation and propaganda work.

"In the UK, this process of evidence-based decision-making is a tradition. "

DEEPTECH: What can you tell us about the UK government's relationship with experts in the outbreak, and how its chief scientist operates?

Chen Zhengming: When there is a new epidemic, the government can not make decisions at the top of its head. It first needs to assess it scientifically. The chief scientist will bring together experts from all fields, including epidemiology, clinical practice, epidemic model prediction, and so on, to come up with various plans and countermeasures. In the UK, this process of evidence-based decision-making is a tradition.

On this basis, the government will come up with a concrete plan of action, which is not purely medical in nature, but will take into account the worst and best outcomes, including the deployment of supplies and defense (community defense, airport security, and so on) . Because pull a start the whole situation, once the decision is wrong or overdo the impact of great. Of course, this plan is not static, it may also be constantly adjusted.

100 years ago, Britain also made mistakes in its response to the Spanish flu. There are two very profound lessons from the relatively despotic society of the time. First, the Spanish pandemic lasted two years, with three waves. In fact, the first wave of influence is not very big, the latter two waves of influence is more. Second, the fear of panic in the UK at the time, but also to block the news, some demonstrations did not cancel the meeting, so to a large extent led to the deterioration of the epidemic and spread.

DEEPTECH: Please talk about the relationship between the Chinese government and the experts, because in the Chinese epidemic, some of the experts have behaved irrationally.

Chen Zhengming: It is very important to have a professional voice. Professional Voice first is to Seek truth from facts, second to timely notification and interpretation of the epidemic and Prevention and control measures. Once the information is out there, people's interpretations won't be that different.

In the early stages of epidemic notification and interpretation in China, the emphasis seems to be on clinical treatment rather than professional analysis and interpretation of the epidemic situation. For example, some people often refer to the so-called inflection point, but there is no clear definition of what is called the inflection point.

Similarly, there is no clear definition of the end of the epidemic. Different standards may be applied in different regions and one size does not fit all. For example, Ebola's outbreak ended when the last patient left the hospital and there were no more patients in the two incubation periods. If there is no clear standard, it is difficult to grasp and control, the people will also produce confusion, the people's livelihood and economic recovery will also bring negative impact.

DEEPTECH: Do you think China is suitable for a chief scientist system like the UK?

Chen Zhengming: it should be possible, not necessarily, to be a scientist, but it should be possible to have a person of high moral standing to play this role. This is not to say that he makes the decisions, because anyone's scientific knowledge may be limited, and he is the leader, coordinating, convening.

DEEPTECH: There have been incidents such as Shuanghuanglian in this epidemic. Why is there such a strong tendency to rush into treatment for acute illnesses in China?

Chen Zhengming: there may be many factors involved, including some cultural factors.

For one thing, the media loves to catch wind, and of course this is also the case abroad.

Second, it's also important for scientists to have control over specific things. British scientists have a lot of media training, such as how to face the media, how to conduct a press release, but also the competent authorities to review and check. To tell a good story, discretion is very important, if mishandled, it will be misleading.

Third, in times of crisis, governments and citizens want good news. Because of this pressure and need, researchers may take shortcuts.

The fourth is conflict of interest. For example, if I run a pharmaceutical company, and I'm also the chief scientist, I might have an interest in selling this. In Foreign Countries, the academic standard is very strict.

And finally, culture. Chinese folk believe in folk recipe and secret recipe. In the history of Europe and the United States there are also traditional medicine and a variety of experience-based treatment. But in recent decades, through the adoption of scientific methods to verify, eliminate the DROSS, false and true, now the treatment is very scientific and standardized. Traditional Chinese medicine is a treasure-house, but in order to carry it forward to the world, we need more scientific evidence, especially the evidence of strict randomized controlled clinical trials.

Brief introduction of Chen Zhengming

(Source: Oxford University)

Chen Zhengming is a professor at the Nuffield College. He graduated from the Fudan University Shanghai Medical College in 1983(now Fudan University Shanghai Medical College) with a Bachelor of medicine degree. He received a doctorate degree from Oxford University in 1992. In 2006 he was promoted to tenured professor at Oxford University School of Medicine. He is currently the director of the China Program at the Nuffield Department of Population Health at Oxford University, an honorary professor at Peking Union Medical College and an associate professor at Fudan University in Shanghai. In 2009, he founded and served as executive director of the Oxford International Center for Population Health Research in China. Research areas include clinical drug efficacy evaluation for common chronic diseases such as stroke, coronary artery disease, cancer, translational medicine, environmental and genetic etiology of chronic diseases, and chronic disease control strategies in developing countries. Over the past 20 years, he has led nearly 10 large-scale randomized clinical trials and epidemiological research projects.
